snippet.textDisplay:
1. 4C hair gets pretty long with proper care, and it's not that rare these days to see women with that hair texture walking around with hair to their butt (though you may only see the actual length when it's straightened). Especially now that perming isn't just the standard of black hair care anymore.

2. That mannequin did not have any coils in her hair, not even on the non blow dried side. You could say that side was wavy I guess, but not coily or even curly.

Brad, I respect that you're a skilled hair dresser and that you try to be inclusive in your videos. However, there are moments when I think you may want to get more experience with black hair before trying to educate others about it.
snippet.textOriginal:
1. 4C hair gets pretty long with proper care, and it's not that rare these days to see women with that hair texture walking around with hair to their butt (though you may only see the actual length when it's straightened). Especially now that perming isn't just the standard of black hair care anymore.

2. That mannequin did not have any coils in her hair, not even on the non blow dried side. You could say that side was wavy I guess, but not coily or even curly.

Brad, I respect that you're a skilled hair dresser and that you try to be inclusive in your videos. However, there are moments when I think you may want to get more experience with black hair before trying to educate others about it.

snippet.textDisplay: Copper is very conductive, second only to silver, so perhaps that is why they used it instead of titanium because it would theoretically be more effective in transferring the heat to the hair from the iron because it absorbs less heat than titanium would (this is why wires are made from copper because it is also cheaper than silver) edit: copper is also more flexible or “bendy” than titanium so that may be another reason
